A language that supports creating functions (and function closures) at runtime. Lambdas are essentially syntactic sugar.<p>This requires a whole different runtime paradigm. If there were examples of code that compiles doing this, which there might be, it would probably be analogous to this:<p><pre><code>  int* getVariable() {
    int x;
    return &x;
  }
</code></pre>
Implementing functions as first-class types generally requires a garbage collector or at minimum a different mechanic than just an ordinary stack and heap. Otherwise, your stack would start to look like swiss-cheese in any moderately functional program.<p>Trying to write something simple, like the Y combinator, leads to a mess like this in C++14:<p><pre><code>  ([](auto f) {
      return [](int k) {
        return ([f](auto g, int i) { return f([g](int j) { return g(g, j); }, i);   })(([f](auto g, int i) { return f([g](int j) { return g(g, j); }, i); }), k);
      };
    })
</code></pre>
While you can find workable examples with template coding (and lambdas), you still won&#x27;t be able to create code like you would in JavaScript for event handlers.

> The big difference with stuff like GC and re-writing stuff in go slowing the compiler time is that they are not inherent to the language.<p>Actually, I think GC is inherent to the language, and that&#x27;s why I listed it as one of the trade-offs that <i>Go</i> made (not the Go implementation made). Almost every language construct depends on GC, e.g. append(), make(), and more. Even the following innocent-looking code:<p><pre><code>  func f() *int {
    a := 1
    return &a
  }
</code></pre>
is GC-dependent, because it would result in a dangling pointer in non-GC languages. But the code is perfectly fine in Go because GC is inherent to the language. It is not possible to make GC optional in Go, so the performance penalty will stay there forever, only alleviated as the implementation matures (or sometimes regressed, as Go 1.5 shows), unless you use only unsafe.Pointer all the time.
